title: static_typename
body:
**Description**: Use a static version of typename.

typeid.name() should result in a constant string if the type being queried is not polymorphic. Some compilers let you use typeid in these cases even if RTTI is disabled (since RTTI is not needed to resolve the string), while others will emit an error.

PR fixes builds in clang, which doesn't allow typeid. It also makes the identifiers more readable/consistent across platforms (GCC/clang spits mangled names, and according to the standard there are no guarantees that the names are unique or useful).

title: Handle nodes with dtype attribute causing diffs in inferred and actual types of NodeArgs due to InsertCastTransformer
body:
**Description**:
 
Generator ONNX ops (RandomNormal, RandomNormalLike, EyeLike, etc.) have the type of the outputs inferred based on a static attribute (`dtype`) and this can cause mismatch between the actual type and the ONNX inferred type of a NodeArg after a pass through the `InsertCastTransformer`. title: Revise pipeline schedule to consider communication ops

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
NCCL is not as flexible as MPI. It requires user to schedule the communication to happen at the right time, so we extend our pipeline-parallel schedule to cover `Send` and `Recv`. The following two tables are visualizations for schedules w/wo `Send`/`Recv`.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3524474/87594658-28d0de00-c6a2-11ea-8ff2-9895e236d4d2.png)

Symbols in the tables:

- FW00: forward compute of batch 00
- FS00: forward send of batch 00
- FR00: forward recv of batch 00
- BW00: backward compute of batch 00
- BS00: backward send of batch 00
- BR00: backward recv of batch 00.

The class `PipelineSchedule` now includes two timeline tables, `compute_table_` and `compute_commute_table_`. `compute_table_` stores existing schedule for backward combability (we haven't replaced MPI with NCCL P2P yet) and `compute_compute_table_` will be used later when NCCL P2P is introduced. Each schedule is a 2-D table. The slot at time `t` and stage `s` locates at `table[t][s]`, which is a `PipelineSlot`. A `PipelineSlot` contains parallelly-computed operations (`PipelineTask`s) such as `Forward` and `Send`.

title: Tensor Creation from data
Check ORT Model Conversion and Preprocessing [Debuggability]
body:
Intention: Pass a single input to an ORT session and PyTorch model prior to any training steps to check that the outcome is the same, indicating that model conversion was successful. This is part of feature #779652, improve debuggability.

Model Cases and Expected Outcome:
1. `_enable_internal_postprocessing=False` and `_extra_postprocessing=None`: only the ort model and the torch model will be compared. Otherwise, the torch model is compared with an ORT model before postprocessing and a distinct ORT model from after postprocessing.
2. ORTTrainer is given an onnx model without any PyTorch model: no comparison occurs.
3. ORTTrainer is given a PyTorch model which includes a loss function. All outputs labeled in `output_desc` are compared between the torch model and the two onnx models respectively.
4. ORTTrainer is given a PyTorch model and an explicitly defined loss_fn: All outputs labeled in `output_desc`, except loss, are compared between the torch model and the two onnx models respectively.

Notes:
- This script has been tested on nvidia-bert (case 3) and a sample example (case 4). It has additionally been tested for a toy bert onnx model (case 2) and with the flags to prevent postprocessing (case 1)
- The PyTorch model is stored on the CPU (may result in better accuracy)
- The tolerance is currently hardcoded at 0.01. Each model output is compared in order with python's math.isclose() function.
- The script will give a warning (and continue training) if the comparison finds a difference greater than the tolerance.
- The currently comparison only occurs before the first training step to check convergence but can be easily extended to further training steps to measure divergence.

```python
import onnxruntime as rt
import torch
from torch import nn

class CrashRepro(nn.Module):

        super(CrashRepro, self).__init__()
        self.img_embedding = nn.Linear(1030, 768, bias=True)

                  verbose=True,
                  input_names=[
                      'img_feats'
                  ],
                  dynamic_axes=dynamic_axes,
                  output_names=targets,
                  opset_version=11)

# works
sess = rt.InferenceSession(onnxfile)
results = sess.run(targets, {
    'img_feats': img_feats.numpy()
})

# crashes
img_feats = torch.ones(1, 0, 1030)
results = sess.run(targets, {
    'img_feats': img_feats.numpy()
})

```

title: Update ModelDescription and minor fix on ORTTrainer ctor
body:
This PR keeps the public API intact, but changes how model description is stored on the backend

Currently, users creates a dict with two lists of tuples. One list called 'inputs' and each tuple has the following format tuple(name, shape). The second list is called 'outputs' and each tuple can be either tuple(name, shape) or tuple(name, shape, is_loss).

With this PR, when this dict is passed in to ORTTrainer, it is fully validated as usual. However, tuples are internally replaced by namedtuples and all output tuples will have tuple(name, shape, is_loss) format instead of is_loss being optionally present.

Additionally to that normalization in the internal representation (which eases coding), two internal methods were created to replace a namedtuple(name, shape) to namedtuple(name, shape, dtype) or namedtuple(name, shape, is_loss, dtype) dependeing whether the tuple is an input or output.

This is necessary as ORTTRainer finds out data types of each input/output during model export to onnx.

Finally, a minor fix was done on ORTTrainer. It could initialize ORTTrainerOptions incorrectly when options=None

This PR is more aimed at discussing possibilities for constexpr construction of OpSchemas than the code itself. The code change is a prototype on how it could be implemented.

Code for registration makes up for a decent amount of code and SymbolSort shows registration functions as the largest ones in the binary. Currently, we build the OpSchema object dynamically using the API exposed by the onnx submodule. Constructing it field by field with individual calls isn't the best for binary size or runtime; furthermore, onnx makes a bunch of copies (they use e.g. strings for storage of text, which while convenient,  will make a copy of the string literals we pass in; it could simply a reference/pointer/view to it instead when we're passing constant, static values).

The proposal is to rewrite OpSchema (and all the objects it contains/receives) to have constexpr variants, and support construction with no copies. Ideally this would be in onnx . In this prototype I made a separate CxOpSchema class instead of editing onnx. CxOpSchema has an API similar to OpSchema, but constexpr. I make an array of constexpr CxOpSchema during compile time, and during runtime I create OpSchemas out of them for registration.

Doing these changes to contrib ops only, I got 48640 bytes saved. More could be saved applying this to all operators, and the conversion from CxOpSchema to OpSchema can be removed if onnx supports this natively.

Ideally, onnx should also have a way to hold a string_view or a const char * to avoid copying of all strings, and spans instead of copying vectors and such. This would make registration cheaper and reduce overall memory usage. I don't know how much of a hassle it is to do these changes to onnx instead of onnxruntime; I'll leave it up to you ORT people to decide :)

The PR is huge since all operators were touched, but the relevant parts are the constexpr classes in the beginning and the conversion from CxOpSchema to OpSchema.

title: WinML should dynamically link against onnxruntime.dll and only system32 for inbox builds
body:
Issue: WinML is layered on top of onnxruntime.dll. On Inbox builds, onnxruntime.dll ships in system32. If the WinML redist is used, a version of onnxruntime (from the redist) is binplaced next to the calling application. This overrides loadlibrary search order, and calls into the Inbox Windows::AI::MachineLearning namespace are redirected to the redist onnxruntime.dll. 

Fix: Onnxruntime calls in inbox builds should always ONLY reference the system32 version of onnxruntimel.dll. To do this, the onnxruntime.dll is dynamically loaded from system32 directly on inbox builds, and using normal loadlibrary search order for redist calls.

title: DirectML.dll is loaded via LoadLibraryW but should use LoadLibraryExA
body:
Issue: Loading DirectML.dll will always use the local directml.dll. Inbox builds should use the system32 version.

Fix: Switch to LoadLibraryExA and search order set to system32 on for inbox builds.
